This paper discusses the evolution of social networks and the effects of diversities of behavioral attributes on social fragmentation. It uses a networked agent-based simulation model to study the topic, which falls under the category of social networks and computational social science (cs.SI, cs.SOC). The paper also mentions the use of theoretical models and the adaptive network framework, which are related to mathematical analysis and modeling (cs.MA). Additionally, the paper discusses the effects of diversities on network evolution, which can be related to cybersecurity (cs.CYBER) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
